project.name: MonkeyBars
project.description: Task library that provides a simple structure for handling singular, sequential and parallel units of code.

TaskGroup.name: TaskGroup
TaskGroup.description:
A task group, and extention of task, provides the building blocks for creating
a group of tasks that is inherently a task itself.

params.name: attributes
params.description: List of attributes to apply to the task group

Task.name: Task
Task.description:
The simplest form of a __MonkeyBars__ task. Once started the task executes all
functionality located within the `performTask` function block. Set `logLevel`
to see console logs during task execution.

params.name: attributes
params.description: List of attributes to apply to the task

ParallelTask.name: ParallelTask
ParallelTask.description:
A ParallelTask is a TaskGroup that runs all of its subtasks ansynchronously. Its
complete functionality is run when all of its sub tasks are complete.

params.name: attributes
params.description: List of attributes to apply to the task group

SequenceTask.name: SequenceTask
SequenceTask.description:
A SequenceTask is a TaskGroup that runs all of its subtasks serially. Its
complete functionality is run when all of its sub tasks are complete.

params.name: attributes
params.description: List of attributes to apply to the task group

classitems.description: Jasmine Spies are test doubles that can act as stubs, spies, fakes or when used in an expecation, mocks. Spies should be created in test setup, before expectations. They can then be checked, using the standard Jasmine expectation syntax. Spies can be checked if they were called or not and what the calling params were. A Spy has the following fields: wasCalled, callCount, mostRecentCall, and argsForCall (see docs). Spies are torn down at the end of every spec. Note: Do not call new jasmine.Spy() directly - a spy must be created using spyOn, jasmine.createSpy or jasmine.createSpyObj.

classitems.description: Blocks are functions with executable code that make up a spec.
toBe: compares the actual to the expected using ===
toNotBe: compares the actual to the expected using !==
toEqual: compares the actual to the expected using common sense equality. Handles Objects, Arrays, etc.
toNotEqual: compares the actual to the expected using the ! of jasmine.Matchers.toEqual

Matcher that compares the actual to the expected using a regular expression.  Constructs a RegExp, so takes
a pattern or a String.
Matcher that compares the actual to the expected using the boolean inverse of jasmine.Matchers.toMatch
Matcher that compares the actual to jasmine.undefined.
Matcher that compares the actual to jasmine.undefined.
Matcher that compares the actual to null.
Matcher that compares the actual to NaN.
Matcher that boolean not-nots the actual.
Matcher that boolean nots the actual.
Matcher that checks to see if the actual, a Jasmine spy, was called.
Matcher that checks to see if the actual, a Jasmine spy, was not called.
Matcher that checks to see if the actual, a Jasmine spy, was called with a set of parameters.
Matcher that checks that the expected item is an element in the actual Array.
Matcher that checks that the expected item is NOT an element in the actual Array.

Matcher that checks that the expected item is equal to the actual item
up to a given level of decimal precision (default 2).

Missing item type Jasmine Spies are test doubles that can act as stubs, spies, fakes or when used in an expecation, mocks. Spies should be created in test setup, before expectations. They can then be checked, using the standard Jasmine expectation syntax. Spies can be checked if they were called or not and what the calling params were. A Spy has the following fields: wasCalled, callCount, mostRecentCall, and argsForCall (see docs). Spies are torn down at the end of every spec. Note: Do not call new jasmine.Spy() directly - a spy must be created using spyOn, jasmine.createSpy or jasmine.createSpyObj.
